ling economy of the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries as a site for revealing how dominant ideas about sexuality are imbricated in Arab American racial histories. Karem Albrecht marshals a queer affective approach to community and family history to show how Syrian immigrant peddlers and their interdependent networks of labor and care appeared in interconnected discourses of modernity, sexuality, gender, class, and race. Possible Histories conceptualizes this profession, and its place in narratives of Arab American history, as a ";queer ecology"; of laboring practices, intimacies, and knowledge production. This book ultimately proposes a new understanding of the long arm of Arab American history that puts sexuality and gender at the heart of ways of navigating US racial systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aPeddlersxSocial networkszUnited States. 0aSexual orientationzUnited States. 0aSyrian AmericansxEconomic conditions. 0aSyrian AmericansxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / LGBTQ+.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520391741zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520391741zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520391741/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA  aZDB-23-UCY